<body>
  <h1>JavaScript Operators</h1>

  <h2>Addition Operator</h2>
  <p>The '+' operator adds numbers together:</p>
  <pre><code>let a = 5;let b = 2;let c = a + b;</code></pre>

  <h2>Assignment Operator</h2>
  <p>The '=' operator assigns a value to a variable:</p>
  <pre><code>let x = 5;</code></pre>

  <h2>Multiplication Operator</h2>
  <p>The '*' operator multiplies numbers:</p>
  <pre><code>let a = 5;let b = 2;let c = a * b;</code></pre>

  <h2>Type of Operators in JavaScript</h2>
  <p>JavaScript contains numerous operator types:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Arithmetic Operators</li>
    <li>Assignment Operators</li>
    <li>Comparison Operators</li>
    <li>String Operators</li>
    <li>Logical Operators</li>
    <li>Bitwise Operators</li>
    <li>Ternary Operators</li>
    <li>Type Operators</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>String Comparison</h2>
  <p>All comparison operators can also be used on strings:</p>
  <pre><code>let str1 = "A";let str2 = "B";let res = str1 < str2;</code></pre>

  <h2>String Concatenation</h2>
  <p>The '+' operator is also used to concatenate strings:</p>
  <pre><code>let str1 = "John";let str2 = "Doe";let str3 = str1 + " " + str2;</code></pre>

  <h2>Adding Numbers and Strings</h2>
  <p>Adding two numbers returns a sum, but adding a number and a string returns a string:</p>
  <pre><code>let a = 5 + 5;let b = "5" + 5;let c = "Hello" + 5;</code></pre>
  <p>Results: a = 10, b = "55", c = "Hello5"</p>

  <h2>Bitwise Operators</h2>
  <p>Bit operators work on 32 bits numbers. ~00000000000000000000000000000101 will return 11111111111111111111111111111010.</p>

  <h3>Self-Assessment Exercise:</h3>
  <p>Multiply 10 by 5, and alert the result.</p>
